---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Card from "../components/Card.astro";
---

<Layout title="Welcome to Astro Cubed.">
  <main class="wrapper">
    <article class="flow">
      <h1>CUBE CSS with Tailwind CSS on Astro</h1>
      <p>
        Simple starter for Astro based on Andy Bell's impeccable work with CUBE.


        <a
          href="https://github.com/hankchizljaw/CUBE-with-tailwind"
          target="_blank">View Andy's original source</a
        >.
      </p>
      <p>
        An example of how you can use <a
          href="https://github.com/tailwindlabs/tailwindcss">Tailwind CSS</a
        > as the U (utilities) in
        <a href="https://cube.fyi/">CUBE CSS</a>. It also uses the following:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <a href="https://every-layout.dev/">Every Layout</a> layouts as
          compositional layouts (the C in CUBE CSS)
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://utopia.fyi/">Utopia</a> for fluid type and spacing
          scales
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://postcss.org/">Post CSS</a> to bundle up CSS files
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        <a href="https://github.com/cubistcastle/astro-tailwind-cube-starter"
          >Check out the source.</a
        >
      </p>
      <h2>Fluid type and space</h2>
      <p>
        This is already being fluidly spaced using <a href="https://utopia.fyi/"
          >Utopia</a
        >, <a
          href="https://github.com/hankchizljaw/CUBE-with-tailwind/blob/main/src/css/global.css"
        >
          global styles</a
        >&nbsp;<em>and</em> a <a
          href="https://piccalil.li/quick-tip/flow-utility/">flow utility</a
        >. Job done. Let’s render the type scale for fun though.
      </p>
      <div class="box flow">
        <div class="text-base">Fringilla Vestibulum Risus Nullam Tristique</div>
        <div class="text-text-6xl">
          Fringilla Vestibulum Risus Nullam Tristique
        </div>
        <div class="text-step-2">
          Fringilla Vestibulum Risus Nullam Tristique
        </div>
        <div class="text-step-3">
          Fringilla Vestibulum Risus Nullam Tristique
        </div>
        <div class="text-step-4">
          Fringilla Vestibulum Risus Nullam Tristique
        </div>
        <div class="text-step-5">
          Fringilla Vestibulum Risus Nullam Tristique
        </div>
      </div>
      <h2>Every Layout Compositions</h2>
      <p>
        I’m not a fan of breakpoint-based layout and as a co-author of <a
          href="https://every-layout.dev/">Every Layout</a
        >, it probably comes as no surprise I use those in projects. Here's a
        couple of handy ones.
      </p>
      <h3><a href="https://every-layout.dev/layouts/sidebar/">Sidebar</a></h3>
      <div class="sidebar">
        <div class="box">I am the sidebar</div>
        <div class="box">I am the content that has a sidebar.</div>
      </div>
      <h3><a href="https://every-layout.dev/layouts/switcher/">Switcher</a></h3>
      <div class="switcher">
        <div class="box">We stack</div>
        <div class="box">
          When there is not enough space for us to be inline.
        </div>
      </div>
      <h3><a href="https://every-layout.dev/layouts/cluster/">Cluster</a></h3>
      <div class="cluster">
        <div class="box">Items that cluster</div>
        <div class="box">But stack where space is limited</div>
        <div class="box">Aenean Commodo Vestibulum</div>
        <div class="box">Ornare Lorem Pharetra</div>
        <div class="box">Fusce dapibus, tellus ac cursus commodo</div>
        <div class="box">Ipsum Etiam Tristique Quam</div>
      </div>
      <hr />
      <p>
        <a href="https://github.com/cubistcastle/astro-tailwind-cube-starter"
          >Check out the source.</a
        >
      </p>
    </article>
  </main>
</Layout>

